17 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
18 SECTION 1. AMENDATORY 2 O.S. 2021, Section 10-9.7, as
19 last amended by Section 2, Chapter 372, O.S.L. 2024 (2 O.S. Supp.
20 2025, Section 10-9.7), is amended to read as follows:
21 Section 10-9.7. A. All poultry feeding operations shall
22 utilize Best Management Practices and shall meet the conditions and
23 requirements established by subsection B of this section and by
24 rules promulgated by the State Board of Agriculture pursuant to the
HB2975 HFLR Page 1
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

CORRECTED
1 Okla homa Registered Poultry Feeding Operations Act. Compliance with
2 a Nutrient Management Plan developed under subsections B and C of
3 this section shall be deemed compliant with Best Management
4 Practices.
5 B. Best Management Practices shall be promulgated by rules by
6 the Board and shall include, but not be limited to, the following
7 when developing Nutrient Management Plans:
8 1. Measures designed to prevent the discharge of poultry waste
9 to waters of the state;
10 2. Measures requiring stored poultry waste shall be isolated
11 from outside surface drainage by covers, ditches, dikes, berms,
12 terraces, or other such structures;
13 3. Measures designed to prevent waters of the state from coming
14 into direct contact with the poultry confined on the poultry feeding
15 operation; and
16 4. Measures designed to ensure that poultry waste handling,
17 treatment, management, and removal shall:
18 a. not create an environmental or a public health hazard,
19 b. not result in the contamination of waters of the
20 state, and
21 c. conform to such other handling, treatment, and
22 management and removal requirements deemed necessary
23 by the Oklahoma Department of Agriculture, Food, and
24 Forestry to implement the Oklahoma Registered Poultry
HB2975 HFLR Page 2
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

CORRECTED
1 Feeding Operations Act and rules promulgated pursuant
2 thereto.
3 The rules promulgated by the Board pursuant to this section
4 shall provide for exceptions to the storage requirements for poultry
5 waste in emergency situations. Such exceptions shall include, but
6 not be limited to, allowing a contract poultry grower to take such
7 actions as are necessary to meet requirements imposed on a grower by
8 an integrator. In such situations, growers shall be required to
9 take all actions feasible to prevent pollution from stored poultry
10 waste.
11 C. Every poultry feeding operation shall have a Nutrient
12 Management Plan which shall include at a minimum:
13 1. A description of poultry waste handling procedures and
14 availability of equipment and type of equipment to be used;
15 2. The calculations and assumptions used for determining land-
16 application rates if land application is applicable;
17 3. All nutrient analysis data for soil and poultry waste
18 testing;
19 4. Legal description and latitude and longitude of lands to be
20 used by an operation for land application;
21 5. Land-application rates of poultry waste shall be based on
22 the available nitrogen and phosphorous content of the poultry waste
23 and shall provide controls for runoff and erosion as appropriate for
24 site conditions;
HB2975 HFLR Page 3
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

CORRECTED
1 6. The procedures documented in the Nutrient Management Plan
2 shall ensure that the handling and utilization of poultry waste
3 complies with the following requirements:
4 a. adequate poultry waste storage shall be provided
5 consistent with rules promulgated by the Oklahoma
6 Department of Agriculture, Food, and Forestry pursuant
7 to subsection B of this section,
8 b. poultry waste shall not be applied to land when the
9 ground is saturated or during rainfall events.
10 Poultry waste shall not be applied to land when the
11 ground is frozen except in conformance with the
12 Nutrient Management Plan,
13 c. poultry waste shall only be applied to suitable land
14 at appropriate times and rates. Discharge or runoff
15 of waste from the application site is evidence that
16 the Nutrient Management Plan requires revisions.
17 Timing and rate of applications shall be based on
18 assimilation capacity of the soil profile, assuming
19 usual nutrient losses, expected precipitation, and
20 soil conditions, and
21 d. poultry waste application shall be prohibited on land
22 subject to excessive erosion;
